{"id":"2301.04789","submitter":"Hunter Monroe","authors":"Hunter Monroe","title":"Hardness of Ruling Out Short Proofs of Kolmogorov Randomness","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cs.CC math.LO","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0/","abstract":"  A meta-complexity assumption, Feasible Chaitin Incompleteness (FCI), asserts\nthe hardness of ruling out length $t$ proofs that string $x$ is Kolmogorov\nrandom (e.g. $x{\\in}R$), by analogy to Chaitin's result that proving $x{\\in}R$\nis typically impossible. By assertion, efficiently ruling out short proofs\nrequires, impossibly, ruling out any proof. FCI has strong implications: (i)\nrandomly chosen $x$ typically yields tautologies hard with high probability for\nany given proof system, densely witnessing its nonoptimality; (ii) average-case\nimpossibility of proving $x{\\in}R$ implies average-case hardness of proving\ntautologies and Feige's hypothesis; and (iii) a natural language is\n$\\textbf{NP}$-intermediate -- the sparse complement of \"$x{\\in}R$ lacks a\nlength $t$ proof\" (where $R$'s complement is sparse) -- and has\n$\\textbf{P/poly}$ circuits despite not being in $\\textbf{P}$.\n  FCI and its variants powerfully assert: (i) noncomputability facts translate\nto hardness conjectures; (ii) numerous open complexity questions have the\nexpected answers (e.g. non-collapse of $\\textbf{PH}$), so one overarching\nconjecture subsumes many questions; and (iii) an implicit mapping between\ncertain unprovable and hard-to-prove sentences is an isomorphism.\n  Further research could relate FCI to other open questions and hardness\nhypotheses; consider whether $R$ frustrates conditional program logic, implying\nFCI; and consider whether an extended isomorphism maps any true unprovable\nsentence to hard-to-prove sentences.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 12 Jan 2023 02:42:51 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 16 Mar 2023 18:26:30 GMT"}],"upda